import re
rows = []
response = requests.get("https://web.archive.org/web/20220518102911/https://www.menuism.com/restaurant-locations/dunkin-donuts-181624")
soup = BeautifulSoup(response.content, "html.parser")
for i in soup.find_all('a', title=re.compile("Starbucks Coffee locations in .*, us")):
    x = i.text.split(" Starbucks Coffee locations ")
    x[1] = x[1].strip('(').strip(')')
    rows.append({
        "State": x[0],
        "Store": "Starbucks",
        "Store Locations": x[1],
    })  
rows = []
response = requests.get("https://web.archive.org/web/20220824121240/https:/www.menuism.com/restaurant-locations/starbucks-coffee-39564")

for i in soup.find_all('a', title=re.compile("Dunkin' Donuts locations in .*, us")):

    x[1] = x[1].strip('(').strip(')')

        "State": x[0],

  1. Scrape the state names and populations from this wikipedia page. Convert the state names to abbreviations and merge these data with your coffee dataset.
population = pd.read_html("https://simple.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_U.S._states_by_population", attrs = {'class': 'wikitable sortable', "style": "width:100%; text-align:center;"})[0]
pop = population[['State','Census population, April 1, 2020 [1][2]']]
pop = pop.rename(columns = {'Census population, April 1, 2020 [1][2]': 'Population'})

pop['State'] = pop['State'].apply(stateabb)
pop = pop[pop["State"] != 'Not Found']

def revenue(coffee_co):
    rev = {'Starbucks': 32250000000, "Dunkin' Donuts": 1370000000, "Peet's Coffee & Tea": 983000000, "Tim Horton's": 3340000000, "Panera Bread": 5795000000, "Caribou Coffee": 262000000, "Au Bon Pain": 351000000, "The Coffee Bean & Tea Leaf": 500000000, "McDonald's": 23223000000}

Are some of these chains more prevalent in certain Regions than others? Possibly despite having less stores overall?

Yes, Dunkin Donuts is more prevalent in the Northeast than in any other region. Dunkin Donuts has less stores than McDonaldâs and Starbucks yet they still dominate the Northeast with the highest amount of stores by far.

from plotnine import ggplot, aes, geom_point, theme

<Figure Size: (800 x 400)>
for i in combined['Coffee Chain'].unique():
    plot = (
    ggplot(combined[combined['Coffee Chain'] == i])
    + aes(x='Population', y = 'Location Count', fill = 'Coffee Chain')
    + geom_point()

    + theme(figure_size=(8, 4))
    )
    print(plot)

For the most part, as population increases, so does the number of locations per coffee chain. McDonaldâs has the most linear increase in location count as population increases. The Coffee Bean does not strictly increase and neither does Peetâs Coffee.
